<br>
The term "under God" in the Pledge was added less than 50 years ago. The term "In God We Trust" was not officially our motto or on our currency until the 50's as well. What was happening in the 50's? You guessed it, Cold War. Who were the Commies? Areligious scum. Politically, to build America itself as officially 'enlightened' compared to the Godless Soviets was just another interesting tactic. <br>
<br>
To those who claim our country was founded by Christians and so we only back tradition: Our founding fathers were by and large Deists:<br>
<br>
deist - \De"ist\ (d[=e]"[i^]st), n. [L. deus god: cf. F. d['e]iste. See Deity.] - One who believes in the existence of a God, but denies revealed religion; a freethinker. <br>
<br>
Considering the era in which our country was fashioned, I see no greater support for keeping phrases like "In God We Trust" and "under God" out of our government than the fact that our founding fathers decided to do so.  Today we are free to interpret all such things as we will though.<br>
<br>
In truth, the religious nature of a country is not determined by tradition, or history, or actual beliefs: It's determined by political savvy and manipulation. We live in a Christianized state due in large part to a backlash against Communism and a re-emergence of a political party squarely based on popular religion (Republicans have to keep their power base, though Democrats are often christian as well). <br>
<br>
The sad thing is that none of our actions over the Pledge, of school vouchers, or anything else relating to dividing the religious and the secular, will be based on anything but the desire to stay in power. The majority of this country is Christian, the minority is not Christian. Christians believe in serving God over country, more often than not, and so how wise is it for politicians to seperate the two? <br>
<br>
Political correctness run amok you say? Let's look at this logically: Minority groups are being excluded. How? Reference to "God" implies a judeo-christian version of religion. Well now, how do I know this for a fact? People have to point to exact definitions of God in order to prove or disprove the all inclusive nature of the reference. The truth of what it refers to is not in the dictionary, but in people's perceptions, and a lot of people feel excluded. Who are a lot of people? No, not a hundred million, maybe only a few millions, maybe even less, but this country was not created to include most of the people. Now, we may say this is political correctness since it's simply a minor offense. Would any one of you consider even the smallest exlcusion by religion to be a minor offense? Do I need to remind you what happened on September 11th, and to what cause they were supposedly pledged? That's right, Allah (not "God"), and we just so happen not to say "one country, under Allah". Small potatoes, right. <br>
<br>
It's easiest to just take religion out of the government. Merging the two not only creates a majority where the minority are considered unimportant, scrambling for the table scraps the government might throw their way, but it also creates a situation where the direction of our secular actions are affeced by religion. Isn't that what we were trying to avoid? Well, maybe not today, since we need 'moral guidance' or some such bullshit in the white house...<br>
<br>
